What is an API?
API (Application Programming Interface) is a way for two applications to communicate with each other using a set of rules.

Simple analogy: You (client) → Waiter (API) → Kitchen (Server)

Types of APIs
1. REST API (Most Common)
Uses HTTP methods, returns JSON. Simple and widely used.
2. SOAP API
Uses XML format. Older, used in banking/enterprise systems.
3. GraphQL API
You ask exactly what data you need — no over-fetching.
4. WebSocket API
Real-time, two-way communication (chat apps, live scores).
5. Open API
Publicly available for anyone (Twitter API, Weather API).
6. Private API
Used internally within a company only.


HTTP Methods
Method    Action             Example
GET      Read data         Get user info
POST      Create data      Register a user
PUT       Update (full)    Update profile
PATCH     Update (partial)  Change just email
DELETE     Delete data       Remove account


